                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120513-52-off292 t18120513-52-crimeloc293"></join>. I am a <rs id="t18120513-52-viclabel294" type="occupation">fancy-trimming manufacturer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120513-52-victim601 t18120513-52-viclabel294"></join>. Howis was my <rs id="t18120513-52-deflabel295" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120513-52-defend599 t18120513-52-deflabel295"></join>, to carry out goods to my customers. I had put the trimmings by<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181205130044"></xptr> in a drawer, because the season of the year did not allow them colours to be wore. They were scarlet and blue. After I had seen them in the drawer I missed them. From suspicion, I had Howis apprehended; and, at the watchhouse, he confessed that he took them, and sold them to Mr. Lee.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120513-52-person605">
                  SAMUEL 
                  WESLEY
               <interp inst="t18120513-52-person605" type="surname" value="WESLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120513-52-person605" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120513-52-person605" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I apprehended Howis. He confessed he took nine pieces of trimmings, and sold them to Mr. Lee. I went to Mr. Lee, and gave him the warrant to read: he produced the trimmings. He said he had bought them of the boy, Howis.</p>
               <p>Howis said nothing in his defence.</p>
               <p>Lee was not put on his defence.</p>
               <p>HOWIS, <rs id="t18120513-52-verdict296" type="verdictDescription">
